{"id":"1302.3015","submitter":"Alistair Rowe","authors":"F. Cadiz, D. Paget, V. L. Berkovits, V. P. Ulin, S. Arscott, E.\n  Peytavit and A. C. H. Rowe","title":"Absence of an intrinsic value for the surface recombination velocity in\n  doped semiconductors","comments":"10 pages, 7 figures","journal-ref":"J. Appl. Phys. 114, 103711 (2013)","doi":"10.1063/1.4821139","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mtrl-sci","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A self-consistent expression for the surface recombination velocity $S$ and\nthe surface Fermi level unpinning energy as a function of light excitation\npower ($P$) is presented for n- and p-type semiconductors doped above the\n10$^{16}$ cm$^{-3}$ range. Measurements of $S$ on p-type GaAs films using a\nnovel polarized microluminescence technique are used to illustrate two limiting\ncases of the model. For a naturally oxidized surface $S$ is described by a\npower law in $P$ whereas for a passivated surface $S^{-1}$ varies\nlogarithmically with $P$. Furthermore, the variation in $S$ with surface state\ndensity and bulk doping level is found to be the result of Fermi level\nunpinning rather than a change in the intrinsic surface recombination velocity.\nIt is concluded that $S$ depends on $P$ throughout the experimentally\naccessible range of excitation powers and therefore that no instrinsic value\ncan be determined. Previously reported values of $S$ on a range of\nsemiconducting materials are thus only valid for a specific excitation power.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 13 Feb 2013 08:38:57 GMT"}],"update_date":"2013-12-17"}
